\section{Study IV: Local Non-Causal Modeling Capabilities}
\label{sec:study4}
A fundamental limitation of standard autoregressive models is their strictly causal, left-to-right attention mechanism. In contrast, \textsc{SDAR}'s blockwise diffusion introduces a \textbf{local non-causal} inductive bias: within each generation block, tokens can attend bidirectionally to one another.
In this section, we investigate whether this relaxation of causality provides tangible benefits in domains requiring structured representations. By adapting a science-specialized AR backbone (Qwen3-30B-A3B-Sci) into \textsc{SDAR}, we isolate the impact of this architectural shift on scientific domains and analyze its synergy with test-time scaling strategies.
\subsection{Structured and General Capabilities}
\label{ssec:science_domain}
Scientific data, particularly in chemistry, often relies on highly structured representations (e.g., SMILES strings and molecular graphs) where dependencies are not strictly linear.
We hypothesize that \textsc{SDAR}'s local bidirectional attention models these structures more effectively than causal masking.
Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide} presents a comprehensive evaluation across 10 benchmarks spanning scientific knowledge, advanced mathematics, and code generation.
\paragraph{Local bidirectionality benefits structured representations.}
The results in the left block of Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide} reveal a distinct advantage for non-causal modeling.
While performance on standard physics problems remains comparable, \textsc{SDAR} unlocks massive gains on {ChemBench (+12.3)} and the expert-level {GPQA-diamond (+5.5)}.
We attribute this to the \textbf{relaxation of strict token-level causality}.
Unlike AR's rigid left-to-right decoding, \textsc{SDAR} enables {intra-block bidirectional attention}, allowing the model to capture local structural dependencies (e.g., molecular topology) without being constrained by sequential generation order.
This effectively allows the model to model non-linear relationships that a strictly causal mask would obscure.
\paragraph{Sequential logic is preserved.}
As shown in the right block of Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide}, this specialized advantage does not come at the cost of general capability.
\textsc{SDAR} demonstrates remarkable stability on logic-heavy benchmarks (MMLU-Pro, AIME), and notably outperforms AR on difficult tasks like LiveMathBench-Hard (+5.3) and LiveCodeBench-v6 (+5.1).
This validates that the paradigm shift changes \textit{how} the model generates text—enhancing its handling of local structures—without disrupting the global causal chain-of-thought logic internalized during pretraining.
\subsection{Diversity and Test-Time Scaling}
\label{ssec:test_time_scaling}
Finally, we examine how the stochastic nature of diffusion-based sampling interacts with test-time scaling strategies. Unlike AR sampling which relies solely on top-$k$/$p$ truncation, diffusion introduces noise at every denoising step, potentially generating more diverse valid trajectories.
Table~\ref{tab:ar_vs_sdar_delta_transposed_subset} details performance under Majority Voting and Pass@k ($k=32$) protocols.
\paragraph{Diffusion noise maximizes ensemble efficiency.}
\textsc{SDAR} exhibits exceptional synergy with scaling strategies.
While single-sample performance is comparable to AR, applying majority voting yields massive gains: \textbf{+19.3 on AIME-2025} and \textbf{+15.7 on LiveMathBench-hard}.
Furthermore, Pass@k metrics reach 93.3 on AIME-2024 and 87.5 on LMB-hard.
This suggests that the non-causal generation process produces a higher diversity of correct reasoning paths ("System 2" thinking). Consequently, \textsc{SDAR} serves as a highly effective generator for ensemble-based inference, converting compute time into accuracy more efficiently than standard AR sampling.


